= Further problems =
Inwagen's claims may gain in credibility because, together with the quibbles
described below, they appear to explain the following claim:
	
	For each belief, and each collection of total evidence it is either
	justified or not to hold that belief. (And holding two mutually exclusive
	beliefs is never justified.) Insofar as one accepts a belief that is not
	justified, one is irrational.

While I disagree with nearly all the chief points in this claim, together they
form something approximting common-sense. Hence Inwagen's claim gains credence
by virtue of apparently offering an explanation of common-sense. It is further
tedious to disentangle all the separate errors in this view, giving rise to the
same difficulties as opposing a [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gish_gallop|Gish Gallop]].

