== a largely independent quibble ==
The paper suffers from the [[problem_with_treating_belief_as_binary]]. The
focus throughout is on "rational to accept p" and never on "rational to accept
p with degree of credence C"

This is manifest in the first section where inwagen argues: that since Ism is
[[#weak exclusivism|weakly exclusive]] then believers in Ism must (on pain of
logical inconsistency no less ) hold that "The teachings of other religions are
at least partly wrong."

Consider the following case. Suppose Aden is a "rational" believer in Ism.
One who has good reason to believe Ism with a degree of confidence that is high
but falls short of absolute certainty. It seems Aden may well recognise this
fact, and hence be willing to assert that other religions are very likely to be
wrong, but still unwilling to assert that the are simply wrong _tout court_. In
hindsight for instance (having since had a revelation of the truth of some
competing religion) Aden might realise that while the evidence available to him
in the past had strongly supported Ism, and hence he had been rational to accept
Ism's truth, in fact Nism had been true all along! But a reasonably undogmatic
believer in Ism may accept that may be in such a position even at the time. That
while their current belief in Ism is rational, it may be that Nism is
(completely) true.

